title: Responsibility to Protect
author: Shivam Agrawal
text:
The Responsibility to Protect is an international coalition that refers to the idea of human intervention under certain criteria describing when, where, how, and by whom intervention could be possible. The Responsibility to Protect, or R2P for short, has had a long history in which the agreement have mainly been based on genocides, and tyrannical killings that have gone ignored by the world while the opposition have used the failures of when countries actually intervened and when countries abused that power.

The idea of countries helping other countries has been existent in Europe for centuries with a book called On the Law of War and Peace by Dutch philosopher Hugo Grotius which was published in 1625, which discusses how intervening to help people resist oppressive government allows for a justified war. About two hundred years later, in 1807, Britain banned slave trade and investigated slave carrying ships travelling away from their own waters, displaying one of the earliest examples of humanitarian right enforcement. Furthermore, in 1994, the Rwandan genocide occurred where one of the two main ethnic groups, the Hutus, killed the latter group, the Tutsis all while the UN remained silent when intervention was necessary on the basis of R2P. Canadas International Commission on Intervention and State Sovereignty dubbed the phrase The Responsibility to Protect and released a report with that title in 2001. The concept was once again brought up at the 2005 World Summit there it was decided that with the permission of the UN Security Council, countries in the UN can legally interfere on the basis of R2P. Furthermore, UN Secretary-General Ban Ki-Moon put forth a report titled Implementing the Responsibility to Protect in 2009 how to approach R2P discussing the responsibilities of the state, when and how to assist, and how to timely respond to crimes against humanity. The most recent success of R2P was the crisis in Libya with the UN Security Council passing the Resolution 1973 in 2011 and ultimately destroying Gaddafis forces.

R2P should be supported to save innocent lives, protect against similar occurrences, to discourage similar acts, to save citizens and their property, to protect foreign consumers, and for world peace. Implementing R2P will require the cooperation of all the nations in the world to decide upon the conditions in which intervention should be approved. Going back to UN Secretary-General Ban Ki-Moon, if the UN approves of his pillars for action, then we can attack in a coordinated and swift way. Ban Ki-Moon described that a State carries the responsibility to protect its populations. If the State is struggling with that task, the international community can assist the State. Finally, if the State fails, the UN must take action in quote timely and decisive manner. This method has already been put into place, again referring to the success in Libya.
